
class Solution {
    public ListNode reverseBetween(ListNode head, int left, int right) {

        // edge case: no change needed
        if (head == null || left == right) return head;

        // dummy node helps when left = 1 (head changes)
        ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0);
        dummy.next = head;   // don't do: dummy = head

        ListNode temp = dummy;

        // move to node just before 'left' (position left-1)
        for (int i = 1; i < left; i++) {
            temp = temp.next;
        }

        // start reversing from 'left'
        ListNode prev = null;
        ListNode curr = temp.next;

        // reverse (right - left + 1) nodes
        for (int j = 0; j < right - left + 1; j++) {
            ListNode next = curr.next;
            curr.next = prev;
            prev = curr;
            curr = next;
        }

        // reconnect the list
        ListNode tail = temp.next;  // original 'left' node
        temp.next = prev;           // connect first part
        tail.next = curr;           // connect remaining part

        // return new head (important when left = 1)
        return dummy.next;
    }
}
```

---

 Note

* Use a **dummy node** to safely handle head changes
* Stop at **left - 1**, not `left`
* Reverse exactly **(right - left + 1)** nodes
* Original `left` node becomes the **tail** after reversal
* Always return `dummy.next`, not `head`
